caah: cdbdisp:00003472:  * the caller's error catcher via ereport(ERROR,...). Otherwise this 
caah: cdbdisp:00003473:  * function returns normally and errors are not reported until later. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003474:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003475:  * If cancelOnError is false, the plan is to be dispatched as fully as 
caah: cdbdisp:00003476:  * possible and the QEs allowed to proceed regardless of cancellation 
caah: cdbdisp:00003477:  * requests, errors or connection failures from other QEs, etc. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003478:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003479:  * The CdbDispatchResults objects allocated for the plan are returned 
caah: cdbdisp:00003480:  * in *pPrimaryResults. The caller, after calling 
caah: cdbdisp:00003481:  * CdbCheckDispatchResult(), can examine the CdbDispatchResults 
caah: cdbdisp:00003482:  * objects, can keep them as long as needed, and ultimately must free 
caah: cdbdisp:00003483:  * them with cdbdisp_destroyDispatchResults() prior to deallocation of 
caah: cdbdisp:00003484:  * the caller's memory context. Callers should use PG_TRY/PG_CATCH to 
caah: cdbdisp:00003485:  * ensure proper cleanup. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003486:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003487:  * To wait for completion, check for errors, and clean up, it is 
caah: cdbdisp:00003488:  * suggested that the caller use cdbdisp_finishCommand(). 
caah: cdbdisp:00003489:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003490:  * Note that the slice tree dispatched is the one specified in the EState 
caah: cdbdisp:00003491:  * of the argument QueryDesc as es_cur__slice. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003492:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003493:  * Note that the QueryDesc params must include PARAM_EXEC_REMOTE parameters 
caah: cdbdisp:00003494:  * containing the values of any initplans required by the slice to be run. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003495:  * (This is handled by calls to addRemoteExecParamsToParamList() from the 
caah: cdbdisp:00003496:  * functions preprocess_initplans() and ExecutorRun().) 
caah: cdbdisp:00003497:  * 
caah: cdbdisp:00003498:  * Each QE receives its assignment as a message of type 'M' in PostgresMain(). 
caah: cdbdisp:00003499:  * The message is deserialized and processed by exec_mpp_query() in postgres.c. 
caah: cdbdisp:00003500:  */

maag: matrix:00000029:  
maag: matrix:00000030:  
maag: matrix:00000031: /* 
maag: matrix:00000032:  * check to see if a int16/32/64 val has overflow in addition 
maag: matrix:00000033:  */ 
maag: matrix:00000034: #define CHECKINTADD(result, arg1, arg2) \ 
maag: matrix:00000035: do { \ 
maag: matrix:00000036:  if (SAMESIGN(arg1, arg2) && !SAMESIGN(result, arg1)) \ 
maag: matrix:00000037:  ereport(ERROR, \ 
maag: matrix:00000038:  (errcode(ERRCODE_NUMERIC_VALUE_OUT_OF_RANGE), \ 
maag: matrix:00000039:  errmsg("int value out of range: overflow"),errOmitLocation(true))); \ 
maag: matrix:00000040: } while(0) 
maag: matrix:00000041:  
maag: matrix:00000042: /* 
maag: matrix:00000043:  * check to see if a int64 val has overflow in addition 
maag: matrix:00000044: * 
maag: matrix:00000045: * Overflow check. We basically check to see if result / arg2 gives arg1 
maag: matrix:00000046: * again. There are two cases where this fails: arg2 = 0 (which cannot 
maag: matrix:00000047: * overflow) and arg1 = INT64_MIN, arg2 = -1 (where the division itself 
maag: matrix:00000048: * will overflow and thus incorrectly match). 
maag: matrix:00000049: * 
maag: matrix:00000050: * Since the division is likely much more expensive than the actual 
maag: matrix:00000051: * multiplication, we'd like to skip it where possible. The best bang for 
maag: matrix:00000052: * the buck seems to be to check whether both inputs are in the int32 
maag: matrix:00000053: * range; if so, no overflow is possible. (But that only works if we 
maag: matrix:00000054: * really have a 64-bit int64 datatype...) 
maag: matrix:00000055: * 
maag: matrix:00000056: */ 
maag: matrix:00000057: #define CHECKINT64MULT(result, arg1, arg2) \ 
maag: matrix:00000058: do { \ 
maag: matrix:00000059:  if (!(arg1 >= (int32) INT_MIN && arg1 <= (int32) INT_MAX && \ 
maag: matrix:00000060:  arg2 >= (int32) INT_MIN && arg2 <= (int32) INT_MAX) && \ 
maag: matrix:00000061:  arg2 != 0 && \ 
maag: matrix:00000062:  (result / arg2 != arg1 *PIPE**PIPE* (arg2 == -1 && arg1 < 0 && result < 0))) \ 
maag: matrix:00000063:  ereport(ERROR, \ 
maag: matrix:00000064:  (errcode(ERRCODE_NUMERIC_VALUE_OUT_OF_RANGE), \ 
maag: matrix:00000065:  errmsg("int value out of range: overflow"),errOmitLocation(true))); \ 
maag: matrix:00000066: } while(0) 
maag: matrix:00000067:  
maag: matrix:00000068:  
maag: matrix:00000069: /* 
maag: matrix:00000070:  * matrix_transpose - transpose an array[x][y] into an array[y][x]. 
maag: matrix:00000071:  */ 
maag: matrix:00000072: Datum 
maag: matrix:00000073: matrix_transpose(PG_FUNCTION_ARGS) 
maag: matrix:00000074: { 
maag: matrix:00000075:  ArrayType *m, *result;

paag: plperl:00000310:  
paag: plperl:00000311: /* 
paag: plperl:00000312:  * Every user function gets wrapped in a second layer so that we can 
paag: plperl:00000313:  * accumulate values returned by "return_next", this also gives the 
paag: plperl:00000314:  * function the "$_TD" which is the tuple description of the expected 
paag: plperl:00000315:  */ 
paag: plperl:00000316: #define USER_FUNCTION_START \ 
paag: plperl:00000317:  "our $_TD; local $_TD = shift; " \ 
paag: plperl:00000318:  "our @_RV; local @_RV = ();" \ 
paag: plperl:00000319:  "sub return_next($) { push @_RV, $_[0] };" \ 
paag: plperl:00000320:  "my $user_function = sub {" 
paag: plperl:00000321:  
paag: plperl:00000322: #define USER_FUNCTION_END \ 
paag: plperl:00000323:  "\n};" \ 
paag: plperl:00000324:  "my @rv = &$user_function(@_);" \ 
paag: plperl:00000325:  "return wantarray ? @rv : $rv[0] if ($#_RV < 0);" \ 
paag: plperl:00000326:  "return [@_RV] if ($#rv < 0 *PIPE**PIPE* $#rv == 0 && !$rv[0]);" \ 
paag: plperl:00000327:  "return [@_RV, @{$rv[0]}] if ($#rv == 0 && ref($rv[0]) eq 'ARRAY');" \ 
paag: plperl:00000328:  "elog(ERROR, 'return must return an array reference when used with return_next');" 
paag: plperl:00000329:  
paag: plperl:00000330:  
paag: plperl:00000331: /******************************************************************** 
paag: plperl:00000332:  * 
paag: plperl:00000333:  * We start out by creating a "held" interpreter that we can use in 
paag: plperl:00000334:  * trusted or untrusted mode (but not both) as the need arises. Later, we 
paag: plperl:00000335:  * assign that interpreter if it is available to either the trusted or 
paag: plperl:00000336:  * untrusted interpreter. If it has already been assigned, and we need to 
paag: plperl:00000337:  * create the other interpreter, we do that if we can, or error out. 
paag: plperl:00000338:  * We detect if it is safe to run two interpreters during the setup of the 
paag: plperl:00000339:  * dummy interpreter. 
paag: plperl:00000340:  */ 
paag: plperl:00000341:
